## 6d Compare models with different degrees of freedom

## 6d.i Construct models

```{r}
mod.ns.2 <- lm(AveBMI ~ ns(AvePM, df = 2) + FemaleUnemp + MaleUnemp + LTHS + 
                 MedHInc + MedHVal + PerBlack + PerLatinx + PerAsianAm + ClimateRegion, data = df)

mod.ns.4 <- lm(AveBMI ~ ns(AvePM, df = 4) + FemaleUnemp + MaleUnemp + LTHS + 
                 MedHInc + MedHVal + PerBlack + PerLatinx + PerAsianAm + ClimateRegion, data = df)
```

## 6d.ii Extract AIC of each model
AIC is a widely used metric for model selection in regression.

It balances goodness of fit and model complexity, penalizing models with too many parameters to avoid overfitting. The model with the lowest AIC is preferred.

```{r}
aic.mod.ns.2 <- AIC(mod.ns.2)
aic.mod.ns.3 <- AIC(mod.ns.3)
aic.mod.ns.4 <- AIC(mod.ns.4)
```

## 6d.iii Put AIC's into a table

```{r}
models_aic        <- data.frame( c("2 df", "3 df", "4 df"),
                                 c(aic.mod.ns.2, aic.mod.ns.3, aic.mod.ns.4))
names(models_aic) <- c("ModelName", "AIC")
models_aic
```
Review pdf of plot: three_ns_model_plot.pdf

::: {.callout-important}
## Class Question 2

Based on the AIC, which model would we prefer?  

**Answer key**

We prefer the model with the **lower AIC** value.

AIC balances model fit and model complexity. A lower AIC indicates a better tradeoff between goodness-of-fit and parsimony. If the difference in AIC between models is meaningful (commonly > 2), the model with the lower AIC is generally preferred.

:::

## 6d.iv `dplyr::select` the model with the lowest AIC here, `which()` identifies rows that meet the criteria and the criteria is having AIC equal to the minimum AIC among the models in the table

```{r}
models_aic$ModelName[which(models_aic$AIC==min(models_aic$AIC))]
```

